So you are not alone in objecting.

@Annar 

The inclusion of a name in a puzzle should in no way be seen as an endorsement of that person.  It's a name, and it's a puzzle.

Mao, Lenin, and Stalin are often in the NYTimes crossword puzzles, and, in general, no one complains. No one sees it as a mark of approval of their lives or beliefs.

@The X-Phile 

The NYT once clued IDI as [A mean Amin]. 

Just to put things in perspective.

@CCNY -- I think that when some people say they have very little on their first pass, what they mean is that they solve as you do, area by area, and after having gone through the entire grid that way, find that they've filled little in.  That is, "very little on the first pass" doesn't automatically mean that they were going through the clues first.

I think people grow into the solving style they're comfortable with, with idiosyncrasies that fit how they think, and what their solving goals are.  One gift of this commenting forum is that you get exposed to different solving styles; you can try them out and see if they are worth doing.  

By telling how you solve in your post, then, you've performed a service!  I solve as you do, by the way, diligently trying to fill in an area following a path created by crossing letters.

